      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Power of Governors</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Adam Giuliano letter says real constitutional crisis over withdrawing troops from Iraq is not between Pres Bush and Congress (March 4 Week in Review article), but between Bush and nation's governors since authority over National Guard is shared by federal and state governments</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''In Wartime, Who Has the Power?'' (Week in Review, March 4): Saber-rattling by Congress aside, the real constitutional crisis over withdrawing troops from Iraq pits the president against the state governors.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''In Wartime, Who Has the Power?'' (Week in Review, March 4): Saber-rattling by Congress aside, the real constitutional crisis over withdrawing troops from Iraq pits the president against the state governors.</p>
        <p>The framers granted the president authority to order troops into battle and Congress the power to finance such engagements. But they also left the states with shared authority over the militias -- today's National Guard.</p>
        <p>By constitutional design, the militias remain a last dedicated line of defense in a dangerous world. But in the modern era, the National Guard increasingly came into federal service as domestic dangers appeared to ebb.</p>
        <p>As we face extended deployments and the ever-present threat of another Katrina or 9/11, today it is the executive power of the governors that most ably can, and should, challenge the war's real costs -- which result from the federal executive's reliance on state preparedness and resources to fight a war overseas.</p>
        <p>Adam Giuliano  New York, March 4, 2007</p>
        <p>The writer, a lawyer, is the author of a recent legal article on emergency federalism in the University of Michigan Journal of Law Reform.</p>
      </block>
